Project: BookSwap – Local Textbook Buying, Selling, and Exchange Platform for Students

Description: Every semester, students spend a lot of money on textbooks they use for
only a few months, then leave collecting dust on a shelf or throw away. At the same time,
other students are looking for the same books but cannot find an affordable option.
There is no easy way for students at the same university or nearby schools to find each
other and exchange books directly. We want a simple platform where students can list
the textbooks they no longer need, search for ones they do need, and arrange a meetup
or trade locally — without paying shipping fees or dealing with strangers far away.

General Needs & Background
Students regularly overpay for new textbooks when used copies are perfectly fine for
studying. Current options like Facebook Marketplace or group chats are unorganised —
listings get buried, it is hard to search by course or subject, and there is no trust system.
A dedicated platform for students, where books are linked to specific courses, would make
it much faster to find what you need. Exchange or trade options (not just cash sales) would
help students who are tight on budget. A local meetup system, such as a suggested safe
spot on campus, would make transactions feel safer than meeting strangers off-campus.

Relevant Stakeholders
Primary users: University and college students looking to sell, buy, or exchange textbooks
Secondary users: University librarians and student union officers, academic advisors
recommending reading materials, student club coordinators
Project stakeholders: Project team, course lecturer, student advisory board
Indirect stakeholders: Textbook publishers and distributors, university administration,
local printing and bookshop owners

What We Want the Platform to Do
- Let students post a listing for a textbook: title, author, edition, condition, asking price
  or trade offer, and a photo.
- Allow searching by course name, subject code, title, or author.
- Show listings from students at the same university first, then nearby schools.
- Let two students agree to trade books without money changing hands.
- Include a simple rating or trust system so students know who is reliable.
- Suggest a standard safe meetup location on campus (library, student centre, etc.).
- Send a notification when someone lists a book you have been looking for.
- Let students mark a listing as "sold" or "exchanged" when done.

Practical Limits We Are Working With
- Students must verify they belong to a university (e.g., using a student email).
- No cash handling on the platform — all payment or exchange is arranged in person.
- Privacy is important — students should not be forced to share their phone number publicly.
- The platform should be free to use for all students.
- Must work well on mobile since most students use their phones more than laptops.

What Good Looks Like
- A student can find a second-hand copy of their required textbook within a day of posting.
- The exchange process feels safe, local, and straightforward.
- Listings are organised and searchable, not buried in a group chat.
- Students save a meaningful amount of money compared to buying new books.